<font color="#FF0000">CHANGING THE RULES</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jul 24  1:15:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I think we could encourage our kids to do things that aren't traditionally part of their sex roles without emphasizing the rules at all. If we try to make family tasks as much a joint effort as possible, so everybody takes part, it seems like the whole notion of roles would mean less. If everybody in the family takes part in cooking, for instance, then the kids will probably see it as silly when they run into the idea outside the family that that's a sex role. There's also a lot of other reasons to doing things this way- many hands make light work, for one.
<p><code>-- fthibau@comp.uark.edu  (Felix) </code><p>


